<HEADLINE>
MOST FEMALE OFFICE WORKERS WILL NOT GIVE UP CAREERS FOR CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 10 (CNA) 05/10/07  18:47:40 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
The majority of female office workers in Taiwan would rather
burden the dual responsibilities of work and family than stay
home to take care of their children, according to the results of
a survey released Thursday by an online employment service.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that among female workers who plan to have
children, 67.64 percent said they will not give up their jobs
after having children, compared with 32.36 percent who said they
will.
</P>
<P>
On the reasons for staying in the workforce, 59.2 percent said
they do not want to become disconnected with society; 57.86
percent said they do not want to depend on their husbands; and
52.51 percent said they hope to have their own careers.
</P>
<P>
Among respondents who said they will quit their jobs, 78.32
percent said they do not wish to miss their children's growth;
68.53 percent said children are the most important thing in their
life; and 23.08 percent expressed worry about finding someone to
help take care of their children.
</P>
<P>
The survey, released ahead of Mother's Day, was conducted by 1111
Job Bank among 2,028 single female office workers between April
25 and May 9. It had a margin of error of 2.2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
As high as 96.32 percent of the respondents said their mothers
have difficult lives, with 60.15 percent saying their mothers
need to work and at the same time take care of their families,
53.44 percent mentioning the heavy financial burden faced by
their families, and 44.73 percent saying their mothers have too
much to worry about.
</P>
<P>
While 65.83 percent of the respondents expressed the intention to
have children, 34.17 percent said they had no such plan,
according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
On the reasons for having children, 70.79 percent of the women
said children are the fruit of love between themselves and their
partners; 53.26 percent said children will make their lives
complete; and 52.58 percent expressed the desire to experience
motherhood.
</P>
<P>
Among those who do not want to have children, 68.75 percent
mentioned the heavy financial burden involved; 60.71 percent
cited the heavy responsibility in raising children; and 33.9
percent said Taiwan's chaotic society is unsafe for children.
</P>
